<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-21T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-21T02:00:00-05:00" n="493" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d493">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/1452: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1" type="from">Adams</persName>) to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-21T15:00:00+08:00">February 21, 1932—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 21—4 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>35. My No. 27, February 9, 5 p.m.<note n="15" xml:id="d493fn15">Not
                                printed.</note> Notice received today from Telegraph Administration
                            that my telegram to <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_OJA1">O’Shea</persName> was undelivered because telegraph line to Kanchow
                            destroyed by bandits. I am renewing representations to Kiangsi
                            authorities.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Adams</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>